===Etymology 1===
From {{bor|en|pt|inhame}} and {{bor|en|es|ñame}}, likely from {{der|en|wo|ñàmbi||cassava}} or a related word. The term was spelled ''yam'' as early as 1657. {{doublet|en|name}}.
====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
# Any climbing [[vine]] of the genus ''[[Dioscorea]]'' in the Eastern and Western hemispheres, usually cultivated.
# The edible, starchy, [[tuberous]] root of that plant, a tropical [[staple]] [[food]].
# {{lb|en|US}} A [[sweet potato]]; a tuber from the species ''[[Ipomoea batatas]]''.
# {{lb|en|Scotland}} [[potato|Potato]].
# {{lb|en|NZ}} A [[oca]]; a tuber from the species {{taxlink|Oxalis tuberosa|species|ver=170624}}.
# {{lb|en|Malaysia|Singapore}} [[taro|Taro]].
# An [[orange]]-brown [[colour]], like the flesh of the yam. {{rfex|en}}
#: {{color panel|CC6600}}
=====Usage notes=====
Careful use distinguishes yams (genus ''Dioscorea'') from sweet potatoes (''[[Ipomoea batatas]]''), while casual American use conflates these.
